Sue Bird acknowledges that she's undefeated
against her former Connecticut teammates this summer and it will
provide her with bragging rights.
article.headline: Storm move closer to final playoff spot
article.linkText: Bird, Storm hand Lynx 12th straight road loss
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Sue Bird acknowledges that she's undefeated against her former Connecticut teammates this summer and it will provide her with bragging rights. Yet there's another thing she's much more concerned with -- winning out and getting the Seattle Storm into the playoffs for the first time. Bird scored 22 points on 9-of-14 shooting as the Storm defeated the Minnesota Lynx 75-63 and her ex-teammates Tamika Williams and Svetlana Abrosimova on Wednesday to give Seattle its franchise-best fourth win in a row. The Storm (14-13) pulled within one game of the final playoff spot in the Western Conference behind the Portland Fire, who are currently in fourth place and were idle Wednesday. Seattle also moved above .500 for the first time since a win at Phoenix on June 14 that put them at 4-3. "It's important we come in and keep the streak going,'' Bird said. "We have a sense of urgency.'' Lauren Jackson added 16 points, seven rebounds and four blocked shots, and Kamila Vodichkova and reserve Simone Edwards each scored 10 for the Storm. Bird shot 4-of-7 from 3-point range. Seattle plays the defending WNBA champion Sparks on Thursday in Los Angeles. Minnesota leading scorer Katie Smith struggled for the second straight game as the Lynx (7-19) dropped their franchise-record 12th consecutive road game dating to a win at Sacramento on June 1. The team returns home to the Target Center to play Phoenix on Friday. Smith finished with 13 points, but connected on just 3 of 13 field goals in 33 minutes. She tied a career low Monday with two points in 35 minutes, shooting only 1-of-15 from the field in a loss at Phoenix. "We did a really good job on Katie Smith,'' Storm coach Lin Dunn said. "She is one of the elite players in the league and we had five people guard her.'' Smith is anxious for Minnesota to fix its problems since the team will be almost the same next season, she said. "It's not like home is any better than away,'' she said. "We've just got to get the job done, and we're not that far away. We've got to do the little things.'' Williams scored 12 points to go with six rebounds. The Lynx shot 33.9 percent to Seattle's 41.7. Minnesota committed 18 turnovers, seven fewer than its season-high 25 on Monday. The Storm outscored the Lynx 26-15 over the final 7:57 of the first half for a 42-29 halftime lead. Kate Starbird, acquired by the Storm in a July 22 trade with Utah, swished a 3-pointer from beyond half court at the first-half buzzer in her home debut. Starbird grew up in nearby Tacoma, Wash., and used to play for the Seattle Reign of the now-defunct American Basketball League. Dunn insisted she didn't know her team's record or that the Storm had won its fourth straight. "The only thing we're thinking about is L.A.,'' she said. "I don't care what our record is.'' Notes
The Storm finished 7-6 in July. ... The Lynx shot 3-for-16 from 3-point range, including 0-for-6 in the first half. ... The announced attendance of 9,686 on a special kids day at Key Arena was the Storm's second sellout of the season.
